B, the ‘codex vetus’ (formerly in the Palatine Library at Heidelberg, now in the V atican) of the 11th cent. contains all 20 plays.

C, the ‘codex decurtatus' (Heidelberg, 12th cent.) contains the last 12 plays only.

D, codex Ursinianus or Vaticanus, 12th cent., contains like C which it closely resembles the last 12 plays with the addition of the Amphitruo, Asinaria, Aulularia, and half the Captivi.

E, codex Ambrosianus of the 13th cent. has the first eight plays including the Asinaria, as has J, the British Museum MS. assigned by Ritschl to the 11th cent., by Goetz and Loewe to the 12th.

The MSS. then in which the Asinaria stands are B, D, E, J, and F1. The extant MSS. present two different recensions of the text. A is the representative of one ε BC the best exponents of the other.
